			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-16167307">
				
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
				
		  
			  <div class="badges">
				  
					  



				  
			  </div>
			  <div class="profile" >
				  
					  


     
        <img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
     







    <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/id/4245363" title="User profile page">lucymutch</a>



				  
				  <p class="date">17 May 2012 3:04AM</p>
			  </div>
		  
		  
					<div class="comment-body">
						
			
						<p>Oh dear, oh dear oh dear, far from the perfect macaron! The shell should be flat and silky smooth. There's no mention of ageing the egg whites, the whites should be separated a minimum of one day and a maximum of four days. Closer to the sell by date the better. <br>When it comes to incorporating the sugar and almonds, it's not about beating, it's about mixing or Macaronage if you want the correct technique. This is why you have air bubbles and some cracking. <br>When piping you need to push down and make small circles to get rid of the air bubbles.<br>After piping and before resting you need to drop the tray onto the work surface until all the bubbles have disappeared, this is your last opportunity to get rid of bubbles before baking and will ensure a silky smooth shell. Resting should be one hour to allow them to dry out. <br>There is no mention in your recipe of humidity. Humidity is everything when it comes to the macaron. Humidity should ideally be at 60 and should not alter too much during the whole process. Close all doors, windows, don't even run the tap. <br>It takes ten years to perfect the art of macaron making. It's a skill and an art that requires extreme precision. Nothing like a sponge cake! I would try writing this article again in 10 years time if I were you.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
